This piece was originally to be added to the book for my son but due to an overwhelming feeling of excitement and closure, I have decided to appreciate it as a work of art itself. Therefore these ideas and logic is also dedicated to the one who inspired them.

Listen carefully. You are not the voice in your head. The voice is just a stream of thoughts, a signal, a pattern, a suggestion. Which is attracted to you based on the previous decisions taken, the previous roads traveled and what we perceive of ourself now. But who you are is what you do about that voice.

The thoughts you receive? They are not from you. They come from something bigger—a universal neural network, a field of energy where ideas, patterns, and responses exist before you even think them. You are just tuning in, like a radio picking up a signal. Think about it. Every thought you have is a response to something that already happened. It’s shaped by:

What you’ve seen and experienced.

What others before you have done.

What the world has trained you to expect.

But here’s where the power lies—you are not just a receiver. You have the ability to create, to interrupt the pattern, to choose a response that has never been seen before.

This means:

· You don’t have to believe every thought that crosses your mind.

· You don’t have to follow every feeling or impulse.

· You don’t have to repeat the mistakes of the past.

Instead, you observe. You recognize that the voice is just data, and you decide how to act based on who you choose to be. That’s real intelligence.

Does that make sense???

Nebulae & The Nature of Thought

Funny how the brain works. I was actually supposed to make this entry about nebulae, but somehow, here we are—already caught in the gravitational pull of a thought.

I was watching some nebulas, and I couldn’t help but wonder—what is that? And why is it so captivating?
There’s a purpose to this, I know it.
Everything has a purpose. Is it space fart?
Is that what happens when planets expel their waste? Or does it hold some hidden significance beyond what I can understand?

And it must have meaning, because we all recognize patterns. No matter where we are, no matter our culture, we see shapes in the chaos. Whether it’s a cloud of gas shaped like a dolphin, the Rose Nebula, or even the simple geometry of triangles and circles—something in us connects the dots.

Now, is this space fart simply air, gas, and dust reflecting rays of light? Or is it angels reflecting down at an angle—the perfect angle—to allow us to make a connection to something new?

Is the space fart baby eggs?
Waiting to germinate?
Or maybe they’re waiting to be pollinated by aliens.
👽

And the reason this matters—why this thought keeps orbiting my mind—is because one night, as I held you(My Son) while you fell asleep, I noticed something. Each time you were close to dozing off, your eyes would lock onto a new object. Intense, focused. Like you were trying to decode something.

Then, I saw it—you were staring at a roll of tissue. Not just glancing at it. You were staring through the bathroom door from the bedroom like it was whispering secrets only you could hear.
And in that moment, I remembered the nebulae…

What is that thing?!?
Is it space tissue?
Does it absorb ultraviolet particles from the environment and teleport the transmutation to another space on a different frequency as Auroras?

I’m sure it will all make sense someday. And I’m not talking about a superficial sense—where science neatly explains that nebulas are just gas and dust.

Because gas and dust is not just gas and dust. Cement and oxygen are gas and dust.
Everything we know—everything we stand on—was once scattered particles, drifting through space.

So maybe nothing is ever just what it seems.
Maybe everything is waiting to be recognized for what it truly is.

So are the nebulas baby eggs waiting to be pollinated by aliens?
An alien entity?
An entity not of pollens.

Because as they are now, the nebulas can only be changed by an external force – something to trigger the next step, something to serve as the initial variance. The missing link. The pollinator.

And after pollination, will the nebulas germinate into planets? Into something new?
Or will they just remain as they are—untransformed, waiting indefinitely for a force that may never come?

Because after interaction with the alien pollen, there will be a reaction — this is inevitable. As the nature of interaction itself implies an essence of compatibility for the nebula to respond.
Meaning that the nebulae is capable of receiving what is being transferred. And therefore this response is what causes transformation.The germination. The moment where potential meets activation. But here’s where it gets interesting—this transformation will either be observed externally as positive or negative. It will produce its first state.

● A positive state means the transformation is open-ended—it can continue, evolve, be influenced further.

● A negative state means it has gone as far as it can go—a dead-end, irreversible, unable to be extended.

Now imagine this:

Adam and Eve eat from the Tree of the Knowledge of Good and Evil… But what if the fruit was actually poisonous? If it was poisonous, whoever ate first would die.
And then, the second person would know not to eat it.

Thus, evolution would continue—but with a new fact: That fruit is deadly.

But the fruit wasn’t poisonous. Because if it was, they would have died instantly.

So what did it do?

It introduced a new state. A first transformation—something that could now be influenced further.
It wasn’t the end of them.
It was the beginning of something else.

How to Think in a World You Can’t See

So now back to the nebulas. If they are baby eggs, then what’s the first transformation? What’s the first reaction? And who—or what—is the pollinator?

Lol. But the truth is, the fact that we are part of the system makes us unable to define it. To define a system, you have to be separate from it— outside of it, looking in. Otherwise, you’re just a piece of the puzzle trying to see the whole picture while still being inside it.

And that’s the problem—we are inside of the puzzle.

No matter how big we build our telescopes, no matter how deep we stretch our theories, we will only ever see what exists within our own system. We can’t see beyond the frame we’re trapped in.

It’s like trying to see your own face without a mirror. You can describe it and guess what it looks like based on reflections, or what your hand feels it looks like -- but you will never truly see it as it is.

And that’s why it is impossible to see the skin of this world we live in.
We can touch it, theorize about it, see sections or fractal fractions of it, send probes and satellites to scan its layers—but we are still inside it. Even if we did reach the edge we would still need a mirror, or a camera with a selfie stick.

A fish cannot see the surface of the ocean while it’s swimming in it.
An ant cannot see the full shape of the earth while it’s walking on it.

Or even like Grand Theft Auto, the characters inside the game can’t tell that they’re in a simulation. They can’t tell that the actions they perform are not their own. To them, their world is all there is. Because how the game works is their way of life. It’s natural to them, even though it is unnatural compared to what the game was modeled after.

A character in GTA doesn’t stop and say:
“Wait a minute… why is it that if I turn this way, an entire city block disappears, then reloads when I look back?”

Or

“How come I can get hit by a car and recover in five seconds?”

Because that’s just how their world works. To us, outside the game, it’s obvious—it’s a simulation, a set of rules, a programmed environment.

That’s like waking one day and saying to yourself… “Why does the Sun warm my face when I look at it…

Or

“How is the water from the sky is just as wet as the water from the ground.”

So now, the real question is: What if we are in the same situation? What if we can’t see the system because it’s all we’ve ever known?

What if the laws of our reality—the things we assume are unchangeable—are just waiting to be unlocked. What if the universe wants us to inspect its code so we can live by it ?

What makes us think we can truly see, understand, or define this system while we are trapped within its design? Unless… unless, we find a way to step outside of it. Or at least a way go deeper within it. To a place where the rules are different. A place where we finally see what this world actually is, not just what it allows us to perceive.

Nebulae and auroras both give us breathtaking displays of color and light, but they are two very different phenomena—one belongs to the vastness of space, while the other is tied to the Earth itself.

But if you look deeper, they might have more in common than you think. Both involve charged particles, transformation, and the interaction of energy with matter. One is celestial, the other terrestrial, but both could be seen as cosmic artwork—patterns in nature’s grand design.

Nebula (Cloud of Gas & Dust)

● A nebula is a massive cloud of gas, dust, and plasma in space.

● It is said to be the birthplace or remains of stars—either forming new solar systems or left behind after a star explodes.

● I’m yet to see a timelapse.

● Nebulae are found light-years across, far beyond our solar system.

Aurora (Dancing Lights in Earth’s Sky)

● An aurora is an atmospheric light display caused by charged solar particles colliding with Earth’s magnetic field. (Cardinal Lights)

● It happens near the North and South Poles—the Aurora Borealis (Northern Lights) and Aurora Australis (Southern Lights).

● Seen a timelapse

● Unlike nebulae, auroras are temporary and constantly shifting.

