The Real Question - Are Nebulae & Auroras Connected
At first glance, they seem completely different—one is an interstellar cloud of gas and dust, the other is a magnetic light show in our sky.

But what if they are just different versions of the same process?

Both are created by energy interacting with gas.
Both glow because of ionization—“charged particles” “colliding” with “matter”.
Both exist because of transformation—nebulae birth stars, auroras react to solar energy.

How me see it, if a nebula is space’s way of painting light on a cosmic scale, then an aurora is Earth’s version—an atmospheric reflection of the same universal stroke.

Maybe, in a way, auroras are Earth’s tiny nebulae, flickering for a moment, mirroring something much greater in the vastness of space and then vanishes away and then returning before it forgets the path back. Or maybe auroras measures the Earths decay?

What If We Are Inside a Nebula

Nebulae exist in space, right? But what if we are already inside one?

What if our solar system is drifting inside an ordinal nebula—so vast that we can’t even see its edges? And the others we observed are nominal nebulas? Idk but it make sense to me. If we were inside a nebula, we wouldn’t even know it, because we can only observe what’s smaller than us or a fraction of what is larger than us, but not the total cosmic structure we’re already a part of. We could actually look like a hammer nebula when we visit the rose nebula.

And that circles right back to the earlier thought;

If we are inside the system, we cannot define the system. So are we looking at nebulae from the outside? Or are we just staring at reflections of what we are already part of?

